Ilha Josina Ivermectin Trial

Preliminary report: cluster identification

Joe Brew and Carlos Chaccour

2017-04-04

Context

This document is a first step in analyzing the feasibility of carrying out an Ivermectin trial in the area of Ilha Josina, District of Manhiça, Province of Maputo, Mozambique. Its objective is to quantify how many clusters of 50 children (age < 5) could be formed, if each of those clusters had a “buffer” of 1 kilometers (ie, minimum distance of 2 kilometers) between two children of two different buffers.

Methods

Census data were used, with a snapshot from May 6, 2016. Residents of Ilha Josina were identified through polgyonal overlay with publicly avaiable administrative shapefiles. Those who were < 5 years of age as of the snapshot date were considered eligible.

A custom algorithm was devised for division into clusters. The algorithm took as parameters multiple different “strategies” for creating clusters (centroid-based, “random walk” based, etc.). A simulations-based approach was used to identify the optimal strategy for the case of Ilha Josina.1 “Optimal” being the maximum number of children/clusters meeting the buffering and age requirements.

Full code for the algorithm and its implementation is available online.2 https://github.com/joebrew/ilha_josina

Results

Of the 934 residing in Ilha Josina as of the time of our snapshot, the maximum number of 50-child clusters we can form is 11 (ie, 514 children).
